# Directory Structure & Mount Configuration

## Step 1: Create a dedicated mount point
```bash
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/nas
Step 2: Configure permanent mount in /etc/fstab
Open fstab
bash
Copy code
sudo nano /etc/fstab
Add line at the bottom (replace with your device ID)
For example: /dev/sda2 /mnt/nas ntfs-3g defaults,uid=1000,gid=1000 0 0
Explanation:
- /dev/sda2 : your HDD partition
- /mnt/nas : mount location
- ntfs-3g : filesystem type (change if exfat/ext4/etc.)
- uid/gid : set ownership to your main user
- defaults : standard mount options
Save + exit.
yaml
Copy code

---

## Step 3: Test the mount
```bash
sudo mount -a
ls /mnt/nas
If you see HDD contents → mount successful.
If error → recheck fstab entry.
yaml
Copy code

---

## Step 4: Set permissions for Samba use
# Give read/write permission to your user
```bash
sudo chown -R pi:pi /mnt/nas
sudo chmod -R 775 /mnt/nas
Final Structure (example)
swift
Copy code
/mnt/nas/           ← main HDD mount point
/mnt/nas/public     ← public share
/mnt/nas/private    ← private share
These will be used in smb.conf later.
